.opencode/skills/cli-devin/assets/prompt_templates.md:18:## 2. Default Coding Dispatch (SWE-1.6, auto mode) — REQUIRES sk-prompt + pre-planning
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/assets/prompt_templates.md:20:> **SWE-1.6 prompt-quality contract**: SWE-1.6 is coding-specialized but smaller than the complex-task models — it relies on the calling AI doing structural decomposition upfront. The framework choice (RCAF primary; STAR fallback, BUILD for multi-file refactor) and the mandatory pre-planning contract are OWNED by [`../../sk-prompt-models/references/models/swe-1.6.md`](../../sk-prompt-models/references/models/swe-1.6.md) (reached via the tier-2 model-override step of the 3-tier precedence rule in SKILL.md §4). Every dispatch with `--model swe-1.6` MUST honor that swe-1.6 profile plus the 3-tier precedence rule (+ CLEAR 5-check) AND include an explicit `<pre-plan>` block before the `<action>` block. The template below is the executor-owned dispatch wrapper around the profile's canonical pre-planned SWE-1.6 prompt shape, using RCAF.
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/assets/prompt_templates.md:22:**Step 1 — honor the swe-1.6 profile + 3-tier precedence.** Before writing the `--prompt-file` payload, consult [`../../sk-prompt-models/references/models/swe-1.6.md`](../../sk-prompt-models/references/models/swe-1.6.md) — the canonical owner of the SWE-1.6 framework choice. The profile sets RCAF primary (the role anchor gives SWE-1.6 immediate framing without burning tokens on situation-setting), STAR fallback for narrative-heavy context-gathering tasks where role framing doesn't fit naturally, and BUILD for well-defined multi-file refactors where scope boundaries dominate — but DO NOT pair BUILD with strict bundle-gate wording (verbose constraint language pushes SWE 1.6 toward defensive output rather than direct code). Run the CLEAR 5-check. If complexity ≥ 7/10 or compliance/security signals appear, dispatch `@prompt-improver` via the Task tool instead of inline composition.
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/assets/prompt_templates.md:24:**Step 2 — compose the prompt with RCAF + explicit pre-planning.** Use this template, filling every placeholder. The framework is RCAF by default (per the profile); swap to STAR or BUILD only if the task clearly fits one of those shapes better.
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/assets/prompt_templates.md:27:<framework>RCAF</framework>
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/assets/prompt_templates.md:81:**Why standard (not strict) bundle-gate language.** Verbose constraint language ("smoke-run required", aggressive anti-hallucination wording, multi-layer enforcement clauses) pushes SWE 1.6 toward defensive output: more disclaimers, more "I can't do this in this session" caveats, less direct code. Trust the framework and the pre-plan to do the work; do not pile on imperatives.
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/assets/prompt_quality_card.md:3:description: "Fast-path prompt discipline for cli-devin dispatches. Frameworks and CLEAR are canonical in sk-prompt; this card carries Devin model-selection mechanics."
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/assets/prompt_quality_card.md:8:Fast-path prompt-quality discipline for cli-devin dispatches. The 7-framework selection table, task-to-framework map, density notes, and CLEAR 5-question check are owned by the canonical card — do not inline them here. This card adds only the Devin-executor mechanics: which Devin model + permission mode fits which task shape.
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/assets/prompt_quality_card.md:12:The 7-framework selection table, the task-to-framework map, the pre-planning-density / bundle-gate / anti-hallucination notes, and the CLEAR 5-question check are OWNED by the canonical card. Do NOT copy them here. The canonical CLEAR (Correctness / Logic / Expression / Arrangement / Reusability) is the single CLEAR for the cli-* family — cli-devin does not define its own.
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/assets/prompt_quality_card.md:14:-> `../../sk-prompt/assets/cli_prompt_quality_card.md`
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/assets/prompt_quality_card.md:15:(deep theory: `../../sk-prompt/references/patterns_evaluation.md`)
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/assets/prompt_quality_card.md:19:cli-devin dispatches several profiled models. Pick the Devin model + permission mode by task shape, then compose the prompt with the canonical framework named below. These rows are EXECUTOR MECHANICS (model routing + permission mode), NOT prompt frameworks — the framework column points back to the canonical card's owned set.
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/assets/prompt_quality_card.md:21:| Task shape | Devin model | Permission mode | Canonical framework | Hub profile |
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/assets/prompt_quality_card.md:23:| Clearly-scoped single-file / small multi-file coding | `swe-1.6` | `auto` | `RCAF` | `../../sk-prompt-models/references/models/swe-1.6.md` |
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/assets/prompt_quality_card.md:24:| Narrative-heavy / context-gathering coding | `swe-1.6` | `auto` | `RCAF` (profile fallback `STAR`) | `../../sk-prompt-models/references/models/swe-1.6.md` |
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/assets/prompt_quality_card.md:25:| Well-defined multi-file refactor | `swe-1.6` (escalate to `deepseek-v4-pro` as complexity grows) | `auto` | `RCAF` (profile fallback `BUILD`) | `../../sk-prompt-models/references/models/swe-1.6.md` · `.../deepseek-v4-pro.md` |
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/assets/prompt_quality_card.md:26:| Security review / RCA / architecture review | `deepseek-v4-pro` | `auto` | `TIDD-EC` | `../../sk-prompt-models/references/models/deepseek-v4-pro.md` |
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/assets/prompt_quality_card.md:27:| Complex refactor with cross-cutting context | `deepseek-v4-pro` (large-context fallback `kimi-k2.6`) | `auto` | `CRAFT` | `../../sk-prompt-models/references/models/deepseek-v4-pro.md` · `.../kimi-k2.6.md` |
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/assets/prompt_quality_card.md:28:| Agentic / tool-use-heavy review (e.g. cross-MCP correlation) | `glm-5.1` | `auto` | `TIDD-EC` | `../../sk-prompt-models/references/models/glm-5.1.md` |
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/assets/prompt_quality_card.md:31:Read the hub profile before composing for any profiled model — it may prescribe a different framework, pre-planning density, or bundle-gate strictness than the cross-model defaults (tier-2 of §3). The SWE-1.6 mandatory pre-planning contract (ordered steps + acceptance criteria + stop conditions + verification) is owned by `../../sk-prompt-models/references/models/swe-1.6.md` — it is not restated here.
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/assets/prompt_quality_card.md:33:### Pre-dispatch addendum — permission mode (Devin-specific, not a CLEAR axis)
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/assets/prompt_quality_card.md:35:Before each `devin --prompt-file` invocation, confirm the permission mode matches the work: `auto` is the default; `dangerous` and other escalations require explicit operator approval recorded in the dispatch log. This is an executor pre-flight check, NOT a competing CLEAR definition — CLEAR is canonical (§1).
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/assets/prompt_quality_card.md:39:The 3-tier precedence rule (fast path -> model override -> deep path) is canonical in `../../sk-prompt/assets/cli_prompt_quality_card.md` and restated in `../SKILL.md`. Apply it in order; stop at the first tier that fully covers the task:
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/assets/prompt_quality_card.md:41:- **Tier 1 (fast path):** build the prompt from the canonical card — select a framework, run the CLEAR check, dispatch.
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/assets/prompt_quality_card.md:42:- **Tier 2 (model override):** when dispatching a profiled model, honor the model profile at `../../sk-prompt-models/references/models/<id>.md` — it overrides the cross-model defaults. (This replaces cli-devin's former "every dispatch MUST be composed through sk-prompt" mandate.)
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/assets/prompt_quality_card.md:47:-> `../../sk-prompt/assets/cli_prompt_quality_card.md` · `./prompt_templates.md` (copy-paste templates + composition patterns A/B/C) · `../SKILL.md` · `../../sk-prompt-models/references/models/` (per-model profiles)
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/SKILL.md:192:> **SWE-1.6 Prompt-Quality Contract (REQUIRED)**: SWE-1.6 is fast and coding-specialized but smaller than the complex-task models — it relies on prompt clarity for reliable output. The framework choice (**RCAF primary**; STAR fallback for narrative-heavy tasks, BUILD for multi-file refactors) and the mandatory caller-side pre-planning contract are OWNED by [`../sk-prompt-models/references/models/swe-1.6.md`](../sk-prompt-models/references/models/swe-1.6.md) (reached via the tier-2 model-override step of the 3-tier precedence rule in §4 ALWAYS). EVERY cli-devin dispatch with `--model swe-1.6` MUST: (1) honor that swe-1.6 profile plus the 3-tier precedence rule when composing the final `--prompt-file` payload, AND (2) include an explicit pre-planning block in the prompt body — the calling AI decomposes the task into ordered steps with acceptance criteria BEFORE handing it to SWE-1.6, rather than asking SWE-1.6 to figure out structure on its own. See `assets/prompt_templates.md` §2 for the executor-owned dispatch template that wraps the profile scaffold, and `assets/prompt_quality_card.md` §3 for the CLEAR 5-check. Skipping this contract is the single largest cause of underwhelming SWE-1.6 output and must be treated as a soft-block in operator review. **Composition guidance** (set by the profile): use medium-density pre-planning (3-4 ordered steps with per-step acceptance and verification); do NOT pair BUILD with strict bundle-gate wording — verbose constraint language pushes SWE 1.6 most strongly toward defensive output rather than direct code, and the same pattern holds on `deepseek-v4` and `kimi-k2.6`, so keep bundle-gate language at "standard" for all cli-devin model presets.
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/SKILL.md:251:Per-model context budget defaults live in `assets/per-model-budgets.json`; the budget pattern is documented in `references/context-budget.md`, and the opt-in output-verification pipeline is documented in `references/output-verification.md`. Shared model facts, quota pools, and fallback targets live in `../sk-prompt/assets/model-profiles.json`.
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/SKILL.md:365:8. **Load `assets/prompt_quality_card.md` before building any dispatch prompt.** Apply the CLEAR 5-check, tag the framework in the Bash invocation comment, and use the returned `ENHANCED_PROMPT`. For complexity ≥ 7/10 or compliance/security signals, dispatch `@prompt-improver` via the Task tool instead of loading `sk-prompt` inline.
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/SKILL.md:366:9. **Prompt construction & model-craft (cli-* family precedence).** Compose every dispatch prompt via the 3-tier rule canonical in `../sk-prompt/assets/cli_prompt_quality_card.md`:
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/SKILL.md:367:   1. **Fast path (default).** Build from the local `assets/prompt_quality_card.md`, which delegates the framework table + CLEAR check to the canonical card.
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/SKILL.md:368:   2. **Model override (mandatory for a profiled model).** If the target model has a profile at `../sk-prompt-models/references/models/<id>.md`, that profile OVERRIDES the cross-model default. The **sk-prompt-models** hub owns per-model prompt-craft (framework + scaffold + gotchas, mirroring `sk-prompt/assets/model-profiles.json` `recommended_frameworks`); consult it before composing for any small model.
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/SKILL.md:369:   3. **Deep path (escalation).** Dispatch `@prompt-improver` via the Task tool (never load full `sk-prompt` inline) when complexity ≥ 7/10, compliance/privacy/security signal, >1 stakeholder, >1 ambiguous requirement, or the fast-path CLEAR cannot clear its floor.
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/SKILL.md:373:13. **SWE-1.6 Prompt-Quality Contract** — the SWE-1.6 framework choice (RCAF primary; STAR fallback for narrative-heavy tasks, BUILD for well-defined multi-file refactors) and the mandatory caller-side pre-planning contract are OWNED by [`../sk-prompt-models/references/models/swe-1.6.md`](../sk-prompt-models/references/models/swe-1.6.md) (per the tier-2 model-override step in rule 9). EVERY dispatch with `--model swe-1.6` MUST honor that swe-1.6 profile plus the 3-tier precedence rule, and MUST still include an explicit pre-planning block in the prompt body: ordered steps + per-step acceptance criteria + stop conditions + verification approach. SWE-1.6 is coding-specialized but smaller than the complex-task models — it relies on the calling AI doing the structural decomposition upfront, so the pre-planning block stays a soft-block in operator review. The profile sets medium-density pre-planning (3-4 steps) and warns against tightening bundle-gate language beyond "standard"; the same defensive-output pattern holds on `deepseek-v4` and `kimi-k2.6`, so keep bundle-gate language at "standard" for all cli-devin model presets. See `assets/prompt_templates.md` §2 for the executor-owned dispatch template that wraps the profile scaffold.
.opencode/skills/cli-devin/SKILL.md:425:- [prompt_quality_card.md](./assets/prompt_quality_card.md) — CLEAR 5-check, framework selection
